---
name: jj
description: Use Jujutsu (jj) as primary VCS interface with Git only as backend/transport. Use for Git-backed jj workflows, bookmarks, revsets, filesets, templates, conflict resolution, multi-remote setup, and Git interoperability. Prefer compact, non-interactive, scriptable jj usage.
---

# JJ for Agents

Use `jj` as primary UX. Use Git as backend, auth, remotes, `.git` compatibility.

## Hard Rules

- Prefer `jj` over `git` for repo mutation
- Prefer non-interactive commands
- Use `-m`, explicit revsets, explicit filesets, explicit flags
- Avoid editor/pager/TUI/merge UI by default
- Use interactive `jj` only if both true:
  1. `interactive_shell` tool exists
  2. `interactive-shell` or `pi-interactive-shell` skill is loaded
- Never run interactive TUI via plain `bash`
- If docs unclear, re-check official docs. Do not guess

## Core Model

### Working copy

- `@` = current working-copy commit
- `@-` = parent of `@`
- working copy **is commit**, not dirty area outside history
- most `jj` commands snapshot working copy first

### `jj new`

`jj new <rev>` creates **new empty working-copy commit** on top of `<rev>`.
Not Git checkout.

Typical cycle:
1. `jj new main`
2. land on empty `@`
3. edit files
4. `jj st` / `jj diff` snapshots edits into `@`
5. `jj commit -m "msg"`
6. current change finalized; new empty `@` created on top

### Tracking model

By default:
- new files auto-track
- modified files auto-track
- deleted tracked files auto-record
- no `git add`
- no normal `jj add` step

Exceptions:
- ignored files not auto-tracked
- custom `snapshot.auto-track` may require `jj file track`
- `jj file untrack <path>` removes from tracking but keeps file in working copy; ensure ignore/snapshot config prevents immediate re-track

### No staging area

Git index habits map to commit-rewrite commands:
- `git add -p; git commit` -> `jj split`  # interactive, avoid by default
- `git add -p; git commit --amend` -> `jj squash -i`  # interactive, avoid by default
- edit arbitrary commit diff -> `jj diffedit -r <rev>`  # interactive, avoid by default

### Bookmarks

- `jj` uses **bookmarks**, not current branches
- no current checked-out bookmark
- new commits do **not** auto-move bookmark
- local bookmark maps to Git branch on push/import
- remote bookmark syntax: `<name>@<remote>`

Commands:
```bash
jj bookmark list
jj bookmark create <name> -r <rev>
jj bookmark move <name> --to <rev>
jj bookmark delete <name>
jj bookmark track <name> --remote=<remote>
jj bookmark untrack <name> --remote=<remote>
```

## Git Backend

### Colocated

Default for `jj git init` / `jj git clone`.
Both `.jj/` and `.git/` present.

Pros:
- tools needing `.git` work
- `jj` auto-imports/exports Git refs on every `jj` command
- easiest incremental migration from Git

Cons:
- mutating `git` + mutating `jj` can cause bookmark conflicts/divergence
- Git often appears detached HEAD; normal in jj
- `jj` ignores Git staging area and unfinished Git rebase states
- Git tools do not understand jj conflict storage well
- many refs can slow auto-import

### Non-colocated

Use `--no-colocate` or `git.colocate = false`.
Use `jj git import` / `jj git export` when needed.
For `gh` in non-colocated repo, docs suggest:
```bash
GIT_DIR=$(jj git root) gh issue list
```

## Safe Defaults

```bash
jj git clone <url>
jj st
jj log
jj new main
# edit files
jj diff
jj commit -m "feat: ..."
jj bookmark create my-topic -r @-
jj bookmark track my-topic
jj git push
```

Generated bookmark push:
```bash
jj git push --change @-
```

## Updating from remote

No documented direct `jj pull` equivalent.
Use:
```bash
jj git fetch
jj rebase -o main
```
If multiple active stacks/bookmarks exist, rebase explicitly per stack.

## Conflicts

Conflicts are first-class commit state.
No `--continue` flow.

Preferred non-interactive flow:
```bash
jj new <conflicted-rev>
# resolve files directly
jj diff
jj squash
```
Alternative:
```bash
jj edit <conflicted-rev>
```
Use only when direct-in-place edit is worth reduced inspectability.

Facts:
- descendants can auto-rebase on top of conflicted commit
- conflict marker style may be jj default / `snapshot` / Git `diff3`
- Git tools often mishandle jj conflict representation

## Revsets

Revsets select commits. Use them everywhere: `log`, `show`, `diff -r`, `new`, `edit`, `rebase`, config aliases, template checks.

### Operator mental model

- `x-` parents
- `x+` children
- `::x` ancestors incl `x`
- `x::` descendants incl `x`
- `x..y` ancestors of `y` excluding ancestors of `x`  # not path-only
- `x::y` ancestry path from `x` to `y`
- `x..` = not ancestors of `x`
- `~x` complement
- `x & y` intersection
- `x | y` union
- `x ~ y` subtraction

Binding: unary/functions > ancestry operators > `~` > `&`/subtraction > `|`.
Use parentheses when nontrivial.

### Core symbols

- `@` current working copy
- `<workspace>@` other workspace working copy
- `<bookmark>@<remote>` remote bookmark/tag
- commit ID / change ID / unique prefixes
- quote symbols if needed, e.g. `"x-"`

### Symbol resolution priority

1. tag
2. bookmark
3. Git ref
4. commit/change ID

For scripts, prefer explicit functions:
- `commit_id(prefix)`
- `change_id(prefix)`
- `exactly(x, 1)` when single target required

### Core functions agents should know

Navigation:
- `parents(x, [depth])`
- `children(x, [depth])`
- `ancestors(x, [depth])`
- `descendants(x, [depth])`
- `first_parent(x, [depth])`
- `first_ancestors(x, [depth])`
- `reachable(srcs, domain)`
- `connected(x)`

Sets:
- `all()`
- `none()`
- `heads(x)`
- `roots(x)`
- `latest(x, [count])`
- `fork_point(x)`
- `merges()`
- `visible_heads()`
- `root()`

Refs:
- `bookmarks([pattern])`
- `remote_bookmarks([name], [remote])`
- `tracked_remote_bookmarks(...)`
- `untracked_remote_bookmarks(...)`
- `tags([pattern])`
- `remote_tags(...)`

Metadata:
- `description(pattern)`
- `subject(pattern)`
- `author(pattern)` / `author_name` / `author_email`
- `author_date(pattern)`
- `mine()`
- `committer(pattern)` / `committer_date(pattern)`
- `signed()`
- `empty()`
- `conflicts()`
- `divergent()`

Content:
- `files(fileset)`
- `diff_lines(text, [files])`
- `diff_lines_added(text, [files])`
- `diff_lines_removed(text, [files])`

Safety/helpers:
- `present(x)`
- `coalesce(a, b, ...)`
- `working_copies()`
- `at_operation(op, x)`

Built-ins:
- `trunk()`
- `immutable()` / `mutable()`
- `visible()` / `hidden()`

### String/date patterns

String patterns default to `glob:`. Also use:
- `exact:"..."`
- `glob:"..."`
- `glob-i:"..."`
- `regex:"..."`
- `substring:"..."`

Can combine: `~x`, `x & y`, `x | y`, `x ~ y`.

Date patterns:
- `after:"2024-02-01"`
- `before:"2 days ago"`

### Revset recipes

```bash
jj log -r @
jj log -r ::@
jj log -r 'remote_bookmarks()..'
jj log -r 'remote_bookmarks(remote=origin)..'
jj log -r '(remote_bookmarks()..@)::'
jj log -r 'mine() & bookmarks() & ~remote_bookmarks()'
jj log -r 'author(*alice*) & description(*fix*)'
jj show -r 'exactly(bookmarks(main), 1)'
jj diff -r 'fork_point(@ | trunk())..@'
```

Guidance:
- use `exactly(..., 1)` in scripts when single target required
- use `present(x)` for optional refs
- use `first_ancestors()` for first-parent style history views
- use `reachable(@, mutable())` for current mutable stack neighborhood

## Filesets

Filesets select paths. Used by path-aware revsets, `jj diff`, `jj file list`, templates, config.

### Pattern kinds

Default quoted path = `prefix-glob:` cwd-relative path prefix.
Useful kinds:
- `cwd:"path"`
- `file:"path"`
- `glob:"pattern"`
- `prefix-glob:"pattern"`
- `root:"path"`
- `root-file:"path"`
- `root-glob:"pattern"`
- `root-prefix-glob:"pattern"`
- add `-i` for case-insensitive glob kinds

### Operators/functions

- `~x`
- `x & y`
- `x | y`
- `x ~ y`
- `all()`
- `none()`

### Fileset recipes

```bash
jj diff 'src'
jj diff 'src ~ glob:"**/*.gen.ts"'
jj file list 'src & glob:"**/*.rs"'
jj file list 'root:"src" ~ root-glob:"src/**/*.snap"'
```

Quoting:
- shell quote whole fileset when special chars exist
- inner quotes required for expressions with operators/functions/meta chars

### Filesets inside revsets/templates

```bash
jj log -r 'files("src")'
jj log -r 'diff_lines("*TODO*", "src")'
```

## Templates

Templates customize output with `-T`. Agents use them for compact machine-readable output, scripted inspection, and precise filtering.

### Core rules

- prefer `--no-pager` with custom templates
- prefer short, explicit templates
- use template methods instead of parsing default human output
- use `json(...)` or explicit separators for machine-readable output

### Useful globals

- `if(cond, then, [else])`
- `coalesce(...)`
- `concat(...)`
- `join(sep, ...)`
- `separate(sep, ...)`
- `surround(prefix, suffix, content)`
- `stringify(x)`
- `json(x)`
- `label(name, content)`
- `config(name)`
- `git_web_url([remote])`

### Commit fields/methods agents should know

IDs/refs:
- `commit_id`, `change_id`
- `bookmarks()`, `local_bookmarks()`, `remote_bookmarks()`
- `tags()`

State:
- `current_working_copy()`
- `mine()`
- `divergent()`
- `hidden()`
- `immutable()`
- `conflict()`
- `empty()`
- `root()`
- `contained_in("revset")`

Metadata:
- `description()`
- `trailers()`
- `author()`, `committer()`, `signature()`

Content:
- `diff([files])`
- `files([files])`
- `conflicted_files()`

Common nested methods:
- `commit_id.short()` / `.shortest()`
- `change_id.short()` / `.shortest()`
- `author.email().local()`
- `timestamp.ago()` / `.format("%Y-%m-%d")`
- `diff().summary()` / `.git()` / `.stat()`
- `list.map(|x| ...)`, `.join(", ")`, `.any(...)`, `.all(...)`

### Template recipes

Short IDs:
```bash
jj log --no-graph -r @ -T 'commit_id.short() ++ " " ++ change_id.short() ++ "\n"'
```

Parent IDs:
```bash
jj log --no-graph -r @ -T 'parents.map(|c| c.commit_id().short()).join(",") ++ "\n"'
```

Description fallback:
```bash
jj log --no-graph -r @ -T 'coalesce(description, "(no description set)\n")'
```

Changed files summary:
```bash
jj log --no-graph -r @ -T 'diff().summary()'
```

Machine-readable JSON lines:
```bash
jj log --no-graph -r 'bookmarks() | @' -T 'json(self) ++ "\n"'
```

Conditional marker:
```bash
jj log --no-graph -r @ -T 'if(conflict(), "CONFLICT ", "") ++ commit_id.short() ++ "\n"'
```

Revset membership check:
```bash
jj log --no-graph -r @ -T 'if(contained_in("trunk().."), "mutable\n", "base\n")'
```

## Multi-remote patterns

Fork workflow:
```bash
jj config set --repo git.fetch '["upstream", "origin"]'
jj config set --repo git.push origin
jj bookmark track main
jj config set --repo 'revset-aliases."trunk()"' main@upstream
```

Independent origin with upstream intake:
```bash
jj config set --repo git.fetch '["origin"]'
jj config set --repo git.push origin
jj bookmark track main --remote=origin
jj bookmark untrack main --remote=upstream
jj config set --repo 'revset-aliases."trunk()"' main@origin
```

## Recovery

Use operation log early:
```bash
jj op log
jj undo
jj redo
jj op revert
```

## Things not to claim

- `jj` has staging area like Git
- `jj new` means branch checkout
- bookmarks auto-move because current branch exists
- documented `jj pull` equivalent exists
- Git submodules / Git LFS / `.gitattributes` / hooks are fully supported
- colocated mode makes Git and jj semantics identical

## Quick Git -> JJ map

```text
git init                 -> jj git init
git clone                -> jj git clone
git fetch                -> jj git fetch
git status               -> jj st
git diff HEAD            -> jj diff
git commit -a            -> jj commit
git branch               -> jj bookmark list
git branch <n> <rev>     -> jj bookmark create <n> -r <rev>
git branch -f <n> <rev>  -> jj bookmark move <n> --to <rev>
git checkout <rev>       -> jj new <rev>
git merge A              -> jj new @ A
git rebase B A           -> jj rebase -b A -o B
git cherry-pick <src>    -> jj duplicate <src> -o <dest>
git stash                -> jj new @-
git reflog               -> jj op log
```
